Course.Title: REPRESENTATION 2: HAND SKILLS
Course.Description: The continued development of refined representational skills is paramount in enhancing the visual language of architecture. Accordingly, drawing from urban situations, the human figure, and still life in different media and at different scales are utilized. Proportion, scale, color, massing and texture are elements in developing aesthetic judgement. Three-dimensional skills in model visualization and execution are also included.

Course.Title: HISTORY 6: RENAI & BAROQ ARCH
Course.Description: Utilizing a travel semester for first-hand investigation of these vital eras in architecture. In addition to enhancing the earlier discourse about their historical evolution, the opportunity for on-site documentation, assessment and evaluation of key architectural monuments is a major factor of this semester. Studies take place in Rome for the Union students, and in New York for Wenzhou students, utilizing examples of Classical Revival architecture in the metropolitan region.

Course.Title: PROFESSIONAL PRACTICE I
Course.Description: The elements of establishing and maintaining a professional design practice are studied in detail.  The relationships with building and code officials, property developers and managers, consultants, and contractors are considered.  Case studies for local models are utilized for instruction, engaging the constituents of a broad professional world to present the elements by which buildings and spaces are conceived and executed in real time.
